 âŠ— IT )X /T . Now comparison of this latter expression with
(18) indicates that an explicit solution via the Eckhartâ€“Young Theorem is not possible unless the
matrix GÌƒ can be written as the Kronecker product of two matrices of appropriate dimensions.
This can happen only under rather special circumstances, for instance, when Î¦ = ÏI. Hence,
the solution is not simple as in the standard independent errors case.
Motivated by a desire to obtain initial estimates for the reduced-rank model (for various
choices of the rank r) which are relatively easy to compute in terms of the full-rank estimator CÌƒ
of model (14)â€“(15). Velu and Reinsel (1987) [9] considered an alternate preliminary estimator.
This estimator essentially is chosen to minimize (19), but with GÌƒ replaced by (Î“ âŠ— XX  /T ),
the weights matrix that appears in (18), the inefficient least squares criterion, with Î“ = Î£âˆ’1
